[{"id":"VR817530","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a diagram and a graph. The diagram shows a magnetic field directed horizontally to the right and a circular coil of wire labeled 10 loops and 0.25 square meters. The coil of wire is perpendicular to the magnetic field. The graph shows a scatterplot of 10 points and a line of best fit. The horizontal axis is labeled time, in seconds, and the numbers 0 to 1.2, in increments of 0.2, are indicated. The vertical axis is labeled B of T, and the numbers 0.0 to 2.5, in increments of 0.5, are indicated. The 10 points in the scatterplot are graphed at 0.1 second intervals from 0.1 to 1.0 and are all very close to the line of best fit, some slightly above and others slightly below. The line of best fit starts at a point with approximate coordinates 0.1 comma 0.2, moves upward and to the right, and ends at a point with approximate coordinates 1.0 comma 2.0.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR817530.g02.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A circular coil of wire with <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"10\"><math alttext=\"10\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>10</mn></math></span></span> loops and an area of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"0.25 square meters\"><math alttext=\"0.25 square meters\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>0.25</mn><mspace width=\"0.2em\"></mspace><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></span></span> lies so the plane of the loop is perpendicular to a time-varying magnetic field <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>B</mi></math></span></span>. The magnetic field strength <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>B</mi></math></span></span> as a function of time <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"t\"><math alttext=\"t\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>t</mi></math></span></span> is shown in the graph. Which of the following correctly describes the induced <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"e m f\"><math alttext=\"e m f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>emf</mi></math></span></span> in the loop for the time interval shown in the graph and provides the correct justification?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR817530_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The induced <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"e m f\"><math alttext=\"e m f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>emf</mi></math></span></span> in the loop is constant and non-zero because the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"e m f\"><math alttext=\"e m f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>emf</mi></math></span></span> is proportional to the change in the magnetic field which is constant and non-zero.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The induced <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"e m f\"><math alttext=\"e m f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>emf</mi></math></span></span> in the loop is constant and non-zero because the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"e m f\"><math alttext=\"e m f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>emf</mi></math></span></span> is proportional to the area of the loop which remains constant.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The induced <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"e m f\"><math alttext=\"e m f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>emf</mi></math></span></span> in the loop increases because the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"e m f\"><math alttext=\"e m f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>emf</mi></math></span></span> is proportional to the magnetic field which increases.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">The induced <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"e m f\"><math alttext=\"e m f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>emf</mi></math></span></span> in the loop increases because the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"e m f\"><math alttext=\"e m f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>emf</mi></math></span></span> increases with each of the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"10\"><math alttext=\"10\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>10</mn></math></span></span> loops of wire.</p>"],"answer":0}]